fr:mainmatter.html:p:
For examples:


The rule instance with the single premise-argument p \;/\; q and the conclusion-argument p \land  q \;/\; r is written as:


\usepackage {ebproof}
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p \;/\; q}
\infer 1[]{p \land  q \;/\; r}
\end {prooftree}



The rule instance with the two premise-arguments p \;/\; p and p \;/\; q and the conclusion-argument p, q \;/\; p is written as:


\usepackage {ebproof}
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p \;/\; p}
\hypo {p \;/\; q}
\infer 2[]{p, q \;/\; p}
\end {prooftree}



The rule instance with the empty set of premise-arguments and the conclusion-argument q \rightarrow  r \;/\; s is written as:


\usepackage {ebproof}
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {}
\infer 1[]{q \rightarrow  r \;/\; s}
\end {prooftree}

fr:resource.fr:resource-source:
\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p \;/\; q}
\infer 1[]{p, q, r, s, p \land  q, \neg  r \;/\; q}
\end {prooftree}

\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p, q \;/\; r}
\hypo {p, q, r \;/\; s}
\infer 2[]{p, q \;/\; s}
\end {prooftree}

\begin {prooftree}
\hypo {p \land  q, r \lor  s \;/\; p \land  s}
\infer 1[]{\top  \land  (p \land  q), (t \rightarrow  s) \lor  s \;/\; \top  \land  s}
\end {prooftree}

fr:mainmatter.html:p:
It is not.
Here's a counterexample: a Boolean valuation v where:

v(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}

v(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}

v(s) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}

v(t) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}
